hands_on_practices.problem:
In dilute non-hydrogen-bonding solution, the carbonyl group of a ketone exhibits a dominant infrared (IR) carbonyl stretching absorption that can be treated, to first approximation, as an isolated diatomic oscillator localized on the carbon and oxygen atoms. Consider three aryl ketones recorded under identical conditions: acetophenone (phenyl methyl ketone), benzophenone (diphenyl ketone), and para-nitroacetophenone (para-nitrophenyl methyl ketone). Assume that any Fermi resonances or strong coupling to other normal modes are negligible for the principal carbonyl stretching band, and that the substituent-dependent changes in the effective reduced mass of the localized carbonyl stretching coordinate are small compared to changes in the effective force constant of the carbonyl bond.

Which option correctly orders the carbonyl stretching wavenumbers and presents a physically sound rationale based on conjugation and substituent effects on the aryl ring?

A. $	ilde{
u}(	ext{para-nitroacetophenone}) > 	ilde{
u}(	ext{acetophenone}) > 	ilde{
u}(	ext{benzophenone})$ because increased $\pi$-conjugation lowers the carbonyl bond force constant, with benzophenone experiencing the greatest conjugative delocalization into two aryl rings, while a para-nitro group on the ring withdraws $\pi$-electron density and suppresses resonance donation from the ring into the carbonyl, increasing the effective bond order and force constant.

B. $	ilde{
u}(	ext{benzophenone}) > 	ilde{
u}(	ext{para-nitroacetophenone}) > 	ilde{
u}(	ext{acetophenone})$ because two phenyl rings exert strong inductive withdrawal that increases the carbonyl force constant the most, with a para-nitro group exerting a weaker effect.

C. $	ilde{
